coping with regular power cuts. It can be very frustrating, particularly when homework is due and the electricity breaks down. Sometimes, if I give in to my frustrations, I wouldn’t get anything done. That is the mistake I made at the beginning of the year. I used to once in a while get bored and give up. As a consequence, I felt like I had less self-confidence, less ability to control my emotions and find myself tempted to harm myself. At school, I’m distant, I don’t like socializing. I’m almost scared to express myself. Adults also seem unreliable. Where do children and teenagers go? There are few politicians and scholars to whom to express disappointment or mistrust.

In your case, the problem isn’t just the power cuts or the overpopulation. It is the fear that fills your heart and mind. Fear gives you no power. It reduces the possibilities that you cannot see. Fear closes your eyes and makes you deaf to possibilities.

When the time came for our internal exercise at the beginning of the conference, I chose a monologue from “Waiting for Godot”. The play is itself a pithy testimony for the hopelessness of George Bush and all third-term presidents. Thus, I had a great time in Rome.
